SQUIRREL POX, RED SQUIRREL - UNITED KINGDOM (SCOTLAND) (02)
***********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Wed 23 May 2007
From: Andrew Greenwood <office@izvg.co.uk>

Readers are reminded that pox in red squirrels has nothing to do with
fibromatosis, but is caused by a parapox virus, possibly originating
in small rodents.
Reference
1. Greenwood, AG: Pox Disease in All Taxa. In: Fowler, ME & Miller,
RE (Eds). Zoo and Wild Animal Medicine, Ed 5, St. Louis, MO (2003),
Saunders (Elsevier Science), pp 737-741.
--
Andrew Greenwood MA VetMB FIBiol DipECAMS FRCVS
International Zoo Veterinary Group
Keighley Business Centre
South Street
KEIGHLEY
West Yorkshire, BD21 1AG
United Kingdom
<office@izvg.co.uk>
[We appreciate the reminder that although the common name is
fibromatosis, it is indeed a parapox virus. - Mod.TG]
